## **Report for Part 4: Model Training (Imbalance Handling)**

### **1\. Objective and Challenge**

The primary objective of the training phase was to develop three distinct classification models capable of identifying the highly rare "Hit" class (only **$\\sim 10\\%$** of the dataset) without being overwhelmed by the majority "Flop" class.

### **2\. Imbalance Handling Strategy**

Given the severe class imbalance identified in the EDA (Point 3), traditional training was insufficient as models would simply learn to predict "Flop" every time (achieving $90\\%$ accuracy with $0\\%$ value).

The solution was to employ **Class Weighting**, which applies a mathematical penalty to the models when they incorrectly predict a "Hit" as a "Flop." This forced the models to prioritize learning the minority class.

The weight was calculated as the ratio of Flops to Hits: $\\text{Weight} \\approx 9$.

| Model | Class Weighting Mechanism | Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Logistic Regression** | class\_weight='balanced' | Adjusts the loss function to penalize errors on the minority class. |
| **Random Forest** | class\_weight='balanced' | Weights the samples used when growing each decision tree. |
| **XGBoost** | scale\_pos\_weight \= 9 | Directly applies a penalty factor of 9 when misclassifying a positive (Hit) sample. |

### **3\. Model Configurations**

To ensure the models were robust and complex enough to capture non-linear relationships, each was configured with specific hyperparameters:

| Model | Key Hyperparameters | Rationale |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Logistic Regression** | max\_iter=10000 | Increased iterations to ensure convergence on the complex, weighted data. |
| **Random Forest** | n\_estimators=300, max\_depth=12 | A deep, large ensemble was chosen to capture non-linear interactions between features like Platform and Genre. |
| **XGBoost** | n\_estimators=500, learning\_rate=0.1, max\_depth=7 | A careful configuration was used: a lower learning\_rate and higher n\_estimators promote slow, steady learning, while subsample=0.8 and colsample\_bytree=0.8 prevent overfitting. |

### **4\. Conclusion of Training**

All three models successfully completed training on the $90\\%$ training subset. The use of class weighting was successful, setting the stage for an evaluation where the models could legitimately compete against the Dummy Baseline's misleading $90\\%$ accuracy. The next step is to evaluate their real-world performance using metrics like **Recall** and **F1-Score**.![][image1]![][image2]![][image3]
